1 What do you understand By Database      
- A database is a place where information is stored in a structured way so that it can be retrieved, 
inserted, updated, or deleted easily

- Example in Real Life
    • Bank systems store customer data in databases
    • Instagram stores user profiles in databases
    • E-commerce websites store product and order data in databases


2 What is Normalization?  
- Normalization is the process of organizing data in a database to reduce redundancy and improve 
data integrity by dividing data into related tables.

- Types of Normalization
    • 1NF (First Normal Form) – Remove repeating groups
    • 2NF (Second Normal Form) – Remove partial dependency
    • 3NF (Third Normal Form) – Remove transitive dependency


3 What is Difference between DBMS and RDBMS?  
• Data Storage: DBMS stores data in files or hierarchically. RDBMS stores data in tables with rows and columns.
• Relationships: DBMS does not establish relationships between data. RDBMS establishes relationships between data tables using keys (e.g., Primary/Foreign Keys).
• Data Structure: DBMS uses a hierarchical or navigational model. RDBMS uses a structured, relational model.
• Users: DBMS typically supports only one user at a time. RDBMS supports multiple users simultaneously.
• Data Redundancy & Normalization: DBMS often results in high redundancy. RDBMS uses normalization to reduce data redundancy.
• Security & Speed: RDBMS is more secure and generally faster for large datasets due to indexing.


4 What is MF Cod Rule of RDBMS Systems?
- Rule 0: Foundation Rule – An RDBMS must manage data entirely through its relational capabilities.
- Rule 1: Information Rule – All data must be represented as values in tables (rows and columns).
- Rule 2: Guaranteed Access Rule – Every data item must be logically accessible using a table name, primary key, and column name.
- Rule 3: Systematic Treatment of NULL – The DBMS must support NULL values to represent missing or inapplicable information systematically.
- Rule 4: Active Online Catalog – Database structure (meta-data) must be stored in an online catalog, accessible via query language.
- Rule 5: Comprehensive Data Sub-language – The system must support at least one language that handles DDL, DML, view definition, integrity constraints, and authorization.
- Rule 6: View Updating Rule – All views that are theoretically updatable must be updatable by the system.
- Rule 7: High-Level Insert/Update/Delete – The system must support set-based operations (not just row-by-row) for data manipulation.
- Rule 8: Physical Data Independence – Changes to physical storage or access methods must not require changes to application programs.
- Rule 9: Logical Data Independence – Changes to table structures (logical level) must not affect application programs.
- Rule 10: Integrity Independence – Integrity constraints must be stored in the catalog, not in application programs.
- Rule 11: Distribution Independence – Users should not know if the data is distributed across multiple locations.
- Rule 12: Non-Subversion Rule – If the system has a low-level (record-at-a-time) interface, it cannot be used to bypass security or integrity constraints


5 do you understand By Data Redundancy?  
- Data Redundancy means the same data is stored multiple times in a database.

- Types of Data Redundancy
• Intentional: Deliberately implemented to improve system availability, such as backups to protect against data loss.
• Unintentional: Occurs accidentally due to poor database design or manual data entry.


6 What is DDL Interpreter?  
- A DDL Interpreter reads and understands DDL commands and updates the database structure in the system catalog (data dictionary).

- DDL commands are used to define or change the structure of the database, such as:

• CREATE – create tables or databases
• ALTER – modify table structure
• DROP – delete tables or databases
• TRUNCATE – remove all records from a table

- How DDL Interpreter Works

• User writes a DDL command.
• The DDL Interpreter checks and processes the command.
• It updates the database schema in the data dictionary.


7 What is DML Compiler in SQL? 
- A DML Compiler converts DML (Data Manipulation Language) queries into machine-level instructions so the database can retrieve or modify data.

- DML commands are used to work with data inside tables, such as:

• SELECT – retrieve data
• INSERT – add new data
• UPDATE – modify existing data
• DELETE – remove data

- How DML Compiler Works

• User writes a DML query in SQL.
• The DML Compiler translates the query into low-level instructions.
• The Query Processor executes the instructions to access the database.


8 What is SQL Key Constraints writing an Example of SQL Key Constraints  
- SQL Key Constraints are rules used in SQL to identify records uniquely and maintain relationships between tables.

- Common SQL Key Constraints

• Primary Key – Uniquely identifies each record in a table
• Foreign Key – Links two tables together
• Unique Key – Ensures all values in a column are different
• Composite Key – Combination of two or more columns as a key

- Example

CREATE TABLE Course (
    course_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    course_name VARCHAR(50)
);

CREATE TABLE Student (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    course_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES Course(course_id)
);


9 is save Point? How to create a save Point write a Query?  
- A Savepoint in SQL is a point within a transaction to which you can roll back later without cancelling the entire transaction.

- Why Savepoint is Used

• To undo part of a transaction
• To control transactions more safely
• To avoid rolling back the entire transaction

- Example

BEGIN;

INSERT INTO Student VALUES (1, 'Rahul', 'BCA');
SAVEPOINT sp1;

INSERT INTO Student VALUES (2, 'Priya', 'BBA');

ROLLBACK TO sp1;

COMMIT;


10 What is trigger and how to create a Trigger in SQL?  
- A Trigger is a database object that automatically executes when an event such as INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE occurs on a table.

- Why Triggers are Used

• To maintain data integrity
• To automatically log changes
• To enforce business rules

- Example

CREATE TRIGGER trigger_name
AFTER INSERT
ON table_name
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
   -- SQL statements
END;